"title": "2233: Son of Man",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "2233: son of man",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A Hebrew and Aramaic term, often used to mean a human being in general. In the Gospels Jesus Christ uses it to refer to himself in his earthly ministry and his future death, exaltation and coming as judge and Saviour.</p>\n<h2>Sons of men as a term for humanity in general</h2>\n<h3>Human beings are inferior to God</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps115:16\">PSA 115:16</a></strong> <em>The Hebrew term here translated “man” literally means “sons of men”. Many of the OT references cited in this theme follow this pattern.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps11:4\">PSA 11:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps33:13-Ps33:14\">PSA 33:13–33:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps45:2\">PSA 45:2</a></p>\n<h3>Human beings are dependent on God's care</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps8:4\">PSA 8:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps36:7\">PSA 36:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps80:17\">PSA 80:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:8\">PSA 107:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:15\">PSA 107:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:21\">PSA 107:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps107:31\">PSA 107:31</a></p>\n<h3>Human beings are mortal</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl9:3\">ECC 9:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eccl3:18-Eccl3:19\">ECC 3:18–3:19</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek31:14\">EZK 31:14</a></p>\n<h3>Human beings are sinful and untrustworthy</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps146:3\">PSA 146:3</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps14:2-Ps14:3\">PSA 14:2–14:3</a> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps53:2-Ps53:3\">PSA 53:2–53:3</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic5:7\">MIC 5:7</a></p>\n<h2>Son of Man as a term for individual men</h2>\n<h3>The sons of Adam</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen4:1-Gen4:2\">GEN 4:1–4:2</a> <em>“a man” is literally “son of Adam” in Hebrew</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen5:3-Gen5:4\">GEN 5:3–5:4</a></p>\n<h3>Ezekiel</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek2:1\">EZK 2:1</a></strong> <em>Ezekiel is called “son of man” 93 times, though this form of address is unique to him in the OT. It may emphasise his remoteness or his humanity.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek2:3\">EZK 2:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek2:6\">EZK 2:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek2:8\">EZK 2:8</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek3:1\">EZK 3:1</a></p>\n<h3>Other people</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job25:6\">JOB 25:6</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan8:17\">DAN 8:17</a></p>\n<h2>A son of man as a ruler of God's future kingdom</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:13\">DAN 7:13</a></strong> <em>The Aramaic “one like a son of man” stresses this person's humanity and mysterious identity</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:13-Dan7:14\">DAN 7:13–7:14</a></strong> <em>He enters God's presence and is given final authority over God's kingdom</em>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:27\">DAN 7:27</a></strong> <em>He shares the kingdom with God's people.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:18\">DAN 7:18</a> <em>“saints of the Most High” have sometimes been interpreted as angels</em></p>\n<h2>Son of Man as a title for Jesus Christ</h2>\n<h3>Used by Jesus Christ to emphasise his humanity and authority</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark2:10-Mark2:11\">MRK 2:10–2:11</a></strong> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt9:6\">MAT 9:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke5:24\">LUK 5:24</a><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark8:31\">MRK 8:31</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke9:22\">LUK 9:22</a></p>\n<h3>The Son of Man receives God's kingdom</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Acts7:56\">ACT 7:56</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Dan7:13\">DAN 7:13</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark14:62\">MRK 14:62</a> parallels <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Matt26:64\">MAT 26:64</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke22:69\">LUK 22:69</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb2:6-Heb2:9\">HEB 2:6–2:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps8:4-Ps8:6\">PSA 8:4–8:6</a></p>",
